>
  <div class="page-content">
    <header class="guide-header">
      <h1>How to Start Investing in Stocks: The Definitive Guide</h1>
      <p class="publish-date">Published: {new Date(meta.published).toLocaleDateString('en-US', { month: 'long', day: 'numeric', year: 'numeric' })}</p>
    </header>

    <section class="intro-section">
      <p class="lead">
        You've saved some money, paid down high-interest debt, and now you are looking at the stock market. You want to know <strong>how to start investing in stocks</strong>, but the financial world is filled with complex jargon, moving charts, and talking heads shouting about the next big thing. It can be intimidating.
      </p>
      <p>
        The truth is, starting your investing journey does not require a finance degree or a Wall Street background. In fact, some of the most successful investors are ordinary people who understand a few fundamental principles and apply them consistently over time. This guide will walk you through exactly how it actually works in practice—not just theory—using real examples, so you can confidently buy your first stock or index fund.
      </p>
      <p>
        Before we dive into the mechanics, let's look at why investing matters. The calculator below illustrates the power of compound growth, demonstrating why getting started early is often more important than the exact amount you start with.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="calculator-section">
      <h2>Investment Growth Calculator</h2>
      <p>See how your money can grow over time with consistent contributions. (This calculator assumes a hypothetical 8% annual return, compounded annually. Historically, the S&P 500 has averaged around 10% annually before inflation.)</p>

      <div class="calculator-card">
        <div class="calc-inputs">
          <div class="input-group">
